9":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"about 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wielher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Merwin, Trud.","perhaps a topographic name from Middle High German <i>wuol</i>, <i>wüele</i> ‘waterhole’ + <i>-er</i>.","habitational name for someone from a place called Wiehl or Wielen (see   Wiehl   and   Wiele  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiehl","meanings":["South German:","topographic name from Middle High German <i>wuol(lache)</i> ‘wallowing place’.","habitational name from any of the places called Wiehl, Wihl, or Wil in Germany and Switzerland."]}]},{"name":"Charles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic word, <i>karl</i>, meaning ‘free man’, akin to Old English <i>ceorl</i> ‘man’. The name, Latin form <i>Carolus</i>, owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the Frankish leader  Charlemagne  (  ?742–814 ), who in  800  established himself as Holy Roman Emperor. His name (Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i>) means ‘Charles the Great’. <i>Carolus</i>—or <i>Karl</i>, the German form—was a common name among Frankish leaders, including Charlemagne's grandfather  Charles Martel  (  688–741 ). <i>Charles</i> is the French form. The name occurs occasionally in medieval Britain as <i>Karolus</i> or <i>Carolus</i>; it had a certain vogue in West Yorkshire from the 1400s, particularly among gentry families. The form <i>Charles</i> was chosen by  Mary Queen  of Scots (  1542–87 ), who had been brought up in France, for her son, <i>Charles James</i> (  1566–1625 ), who became  King James VI  of Scotland and, from  1603 ,  James I  of England. His son and grandson both reigned as  King Charles , and the name thus became established in the 17th century both in the Stuart royal house and among English and Scottish supporters of the Stuart monarchy. In the 18th century it was to some extent favoured, along with   James  , by Jacobites, supporters of the exiled Stuarts, opposed to the Hanoverian monarchy, especially in the Highlands of Scotland. In the 19th century the popularity of the name was further enhanced by romanticization of the story of ‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’, leader of the  1745  rebellion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Charles Thomas Wielher was born in 1167, in England, his father, Sir Edward Thomas Wielher II, was 28 and his mother, Elizabeth Toriey, was 23. He married Carah Terry Hains about 1198, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1210, in his hometown, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"umbes 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"fi":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"noin 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"fr":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"environ 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Charles Thomas Wielher est né en 1167, à Angleterre, son père, Sir Edward Thomas Wielher II, avait 28 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth Toriey, avait 23 ans. Il a épousé Carah Terry Hains environ 1198, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1210, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 43 ans."},"de":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"um 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Als Charles Thomas Wielher 1167 in England geboren wurde, war sein Vater Sir Edward Thomas Wielher II 28 und seine Mutter Elizabeth Toriey 23. Er hat um 1198 in England Carah Terry Hains geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1210 im Alter von 43 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"about 1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"hu":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1139–1185":"1139–1185","1144–1180":"1144–1180","1139":"1139","1169":"1169","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","about 1198":"1198 körül","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","England":"England"},"id":{"1167–1210":"1167–1210","1169–1220":"1169–1220